      <div xml:id="NA341-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaivayiṉ pirintu āṟṟāṉākiya talaimakaṉ (ET: pācaṟaikkaṇ iruntu) colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said who was unable to bear it when separating for the sake of wealth.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA341">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vaṅkavarip pāṟaic ciṟupāṭu muṇaiyiṟ</l>
<l>            cempoṟi yarakkiṉ vaṭṭunā vaṭikkum</l>
<l>            viḷaiyā ṭiṉṉakai yaḻuṅkāp pāṉmaṭut</l>
<l>            talaiyā vulavai yōcciccila kiḷaiyāk</l>
<l>            kuṉṟak kuṟavaṉoṭu kuṟunoṭi payiṟṟun</l>
<l>            tuṇainaṉ kuṭaiyaṇ maṭantai yāmē</l>
<l>            vempakai yarumuṉait taṇpeyal poḻinteṉa</l>
<l>            nīriraṅ karaināṇ mayaṅkik kūtiroṭu</l>
<l>            vēṟupula vāṭai yalaippat</l>
<l>            tuṇaiyilēn tamiyēm pācaṟai yēmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The girl well possesses a companion,</l>
<l rend="indent">who, if she has enough of [her] little sleep on the silver-lined rock,</l>
<l rend="indent">drinks the unspoiled milk<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aḻuṅkā pāl</term> is here interpreted by T.V.G. as toddy which might make more sense in the context of the description of a part of the vessel.</note>, with a playful sweet smile,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that she causes to flow from the round tongue of red-spotted vermilion,</l>
<l rend="indent">raises, without slapping, a green twig, deals [him] a few [mock blows](?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kiḷaiyā</term> is a problem. It seems to be the absolutive (either negative or positive) of a root <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷai</term>, but the only item given by the TL is a 4th class verb connected with the idea of cleaning something (and is not recorded by the DEDR). Perhaps cleaning is here used in a transferred meaning of threatening to punish someone with the twig. T.V.G., however, interprets the word as "talking", of which there is no trace in the TL. (Does he mix it up with <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷa</term>?)</note></l>
<l rend="indent">and repeats short phrases with the man from the hills.<note place="foot">So this is the erotic reading of the first half: HE watches a woman with her lover and is reminded of his own woman. There is a second interpretation of this as a play between mother and son (who has to be coaxed quite forcefully to drink his milk - a topos familiar from the elopement poems). The only problem with this is <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟavaṉ</term>. This is definitely not a designation for a son.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">We,</l>
<l rend="indent">while the north wind from other fields dashes along</l>
<l rend="indent">with the cold season, half-days diffuse with water wailing(?),</l>
<l rend="indent2">because cool rain has flown on the difficult front of hot enmity,</l>
<l>we are without companion, we [are] solitary, we [are] in the encampment.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
